05240nam a22008775i 9783110424447DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20162016gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2016013327  a(OCoLC)958420130  a97831104244477 a10.1515/97831104244472doi  a(DE-B1597)451939  a(OCoLC)954883047  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aB2949.M4bH435 2014 4aB2949.M4 7aPHI0130002bisacsh04a19322300aHegel and Metaphysics :bOn Logic and Ontology in the System /cAllegra de Laurentiis. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (VII, 233 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHegel-Jahrbuch Sonderband ;v700tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tHegel’s Concept of the True Infinite and the Idea of a post-Critical Metaphysics -- tA Deflationary Approach to Hegel’s Metaphysics -- tHegel as Metaphysician -- tHegel’s Overcoming of the Overcoming of Metaphysics -- tA Critique of Non-Metaphysical Readings of Hegel’s Practical Philosophy -- tThe Metaphysical Presuppositions of Hegel’s Philosophy of Self-Consciousness -- tThe Interplay Between Logic and Metaphysics -- tHegel’s Metaphysics -- tHegel’s Faith and Knowledge and the Metaphysics that Takes the Place of Metaphysics -- tHegel’s Metaphysics as Speculative Naturalism -- tHegel’s Metaphysics of Action -- tOn the Limits of Language in a Hegelian Metaphysics -- tThe German Ideology and the Sublation of Idealism -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe collective focus of the essays here presented consists of the attempt to overcome the deadlock between metaphysical and non- (or anti-) metaphysical Hegel interpretations. There is no doubt that Hegel rejects traditional and influential forms of metaphysical thought. There is also no doubt that he grounds his philosophical system on a metaphysical theory of thought and reality. The question asked by the contributors in this volume is therefore: what kind of metaphysics does Hegel reject, and what kind does he embrace? Some of the papers address the issue in general and comprehensive terms, but from different, even opposite perspectives: Hegel's claim of a ‘unity’ of logic and metaphysics; his potentially deflationary understanding of metaphysics; his overt metaphysical commitments; his subject-less notion of logical thought; and his criticism of Kant's critique of metaphysics. Other contributors discuss the same topics in view of very specific subject-matter in Hegel's corpus, to wit: the philosophy of self-consciousness; practical philosophy; teleology and holism; a particular brand of naturalism; language's relation to thought; 'true' and ‘spurious’ infinity as pivotal in philosophic thinking; and Hegel's conception of human agency and action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aMetaphysicsvCongresses. 0aMetaphysicsxCongresses. 4aDeutscher Idealismus. 4aHegel, Georg Wilhelm Friedrich. 4aIdealism. 4aMetaphysik. 4aOntologie. 4ametaphysics. 4aontology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Metaphysics.2bisacsh1 aLaurentiis, Allegra de, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWhited, Soren08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2016z9783110485301oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831104246380 cprintz978311042723340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311042444740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110424447423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/co